This looks fine to me. I've left a bunch of comments, mostly superficial. I'm reluctant to merge this myself because you're my Masters student...
I assume this is not intended to be here?
Yes I forgot it's there :))

Is this ordering of the `c` constants arbitrary, or an obvious one? If you chose it arbitrarily, I'd argue it's better to keep the original order so that we can have the last value default to zero; but if this order is obviously the"right" one, then fine as is.
I'm not sure about the "right" one, I made this order so that it's the same with the way it's defined in Bourbaki
Also this reminded me to change the docstring in this instance thanks :))
One argument against your order is that what you call `c` is what wikipedia calls `b`

![bourbaki](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6c8b4003-73a1-4db1-b655-ea1480bbd0e3)
Is it this one you're asking?

Just to summarise the change: it used to be that i^2=a and j^2=b but this does not capture all quaternion algebras in characteristic 2; it is now i^2=a+bi and j^2=c so it does feel weird putting the new variable at the end :-(
I think at least the doc should not use the wikipedia page as the primary reference, given it now diverges from it.
I've changed the reference to Bourbaki
I would not remove the equations explaining what a,b,c are; why not say $i^2=ai+b$ and $j^2=c$ or whatever the conventions are now?
Done!
If you're going to use `simp` then you probably don't need to rewrite `neg_zero` and maybe some other theorems can be removed from the `rw`.
turns out `rw` was totally redundant...

This is no longer an adequate reference because Wikipedia only deals with the case of characteristic not 2. Maybe it's just better to say i^2=a+bi and j^2=c and ij=-ji?

It might also be good to explain that many references (for example Wikipedia) assume char != 2 in which case one can complete the square and assume b = 0 but you're following Bourbaki who work in the general setting.
Yep deleted the wiki as reference added Bourbaki
Maybe remark that this is not a particularly well-behaved definition unless c_2=0?
good idea
What behaves poorly about it?

If c_2=0 and if 2!=0 then the star operator is an involution on the space of quaternions, and it has a 1-dimensional +1 eigenspace (the "real" quaternions) and a 3-dimensional -1-eigenspace (the "imaginary" part), so one can argue that the real and imaginary parts of a quaternion are a very natural decomposition in this setting. But if c_2 isn't 0 then it's still true that the star of a real quaternion is real but it is no longer true that the star of an "imaginary" (in this sense) quaternion is always imaginary, and the more conceptually useful concept is the -1 eigenspace for star (just like the imaginary part of a complex number is the part where complex conjugation acts as -1). In practice this just means that a bunch of theorems about im are going to be false unless we add the hypothesis c_2=0.
Let's try and condense this into the docstring, perhaps as in my suggestion in the line above.
judging by the diff these last three lines should be indented two characters more.
done!

```suggestion
  quaternion algebra if `c₂` is 0. -/
```
Unresolving, I agree with Kevin.
This proof might be brittle now, I'm not sure. What is `simp` doing that `simp only` is not? Aren't several of those lemmas you're using simp lemmas anyway?
hmmm actually I could just use `simp` and then `linear_combination` does this count as non-terminal `simp`? Not entirely sure.
There is some consensus about this now (but I don't know what it is). Just go for `simp <;> linear_combination` if it works; `simp <;> ring` is allowed and this is very close to that.
yeah `simp <;> linear_combination` works
Does `by exact?` come up with anything?
no `exact?` gives nothing... :-(
What is the statement that needs to be proved? I'm talking about the `rfl` which changed to `by simp`
the statement is `(star (s • a)).re = (s • star a).re`
I think it's no longer `rfl` because `star a` is not `⟨a.1, -a.2, -a.3, -a.4⟩` anymore
Does `by simp` work? Same for the below. There's no point doing `simp [list including a bunch of simp lemmas]`.
`ring` solves everything! :))
What happened here? Does the fact that you needed `rfl` indicate that there's a missing `simp` lemma?
I think `rfl` here is for `lean` to understand `ℍ[R]` is the same as `ℍ[R,-1,0,-1]`, I haven't found a way to avoid it though...
okay changing `def Quaternion.coe` to `abbrev` solves it!

```suggestion
  the square and WLOG assume $b = 0$.)
```
Can we keep ``ℍ[R, c₁, c₃]`` as a deprecated version of ``ℍ[R, c₁, 0, c₃]``?
how do I deprecate something? just add `@[deprecated]`?
Kevin suggested that we keep both notation and I think that's a good idea?
Perhaps `` `charR ≠ 2` `` or `$\operatorname{char} R ≠ 2$` for formatting; or however you would usually write this in LaTeX.
Okay done!

I don't think we need this level of detail here; perhaps
```suggestion
@[inherit_doc, deprecated "Use ℍ[R,a,0,b] instead of ℍ[R,a,b]." (since := "2025-01-15")]
```

@kbuzzard, is this a good summary?
```suggestion
/-- The imaginary part of a quaternion.

Note that unless `c₂ = 0`, this definition is not particularly well-behaved;
for instance, `QuaternionAlgebra.star_im` only says that the star of an imaginary quaternions
is imaginary under this condition. -/
```

bors d=@kbuzzard

Just to check you saw this.

Thanks @Whysoserioushah!

> bors d=@kbuzzard
> 
> Just to check you saw this.
> 
> Thanks @Whysoserioushah!

Thanks Eric! :))
Sorry, I've been picking up the pieces since Lean Together and haven't been looking at github at all. I've just reviewed the entire PR again and I'm now happy.

```suggestion
    mk
      (a₁ * b₁ + c₁ * a₂ * b₂ + c₃ * a₃ * b₃ + c₂ * c₃ * a₃ * b₄ - c₁ * c₃ * a₄ * b₄)
      (a₁ * b₂ + a₂ * b₁ + c₂ * a₂ * b₂ - c₃ * a₃ * b₄ + c₃ * a₄ * b₃)
      (a₁ * b₃ + c₁ * a₂ * b₄ + a₃ * b₁ + c₂ * a₃ * b₂ - c₁ * a₄ * b₂)
      (a₁ * b₄ + a₂ * b₃ + c₂ * a₂ * b₄ - a₃ * b₂ + a₄ * b₁) :=
```
Why do we now need both theorems?

I think this is linked to the [unrelated change](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20657/files#r1920265194) you made above; both should live in the same, separate, PR. Up to you if you'd like it to be merged before or after this one.
I now understand what you were aiming for here, I've added a docstring accordingly.
Yeah it's generalisation in two different directions so I guess both is necessary? :))
Yeah it feels to me like kind of a miracle that a random action on R would commute with star!
This looks like a bad lemma to me, the LHS and RHS have different types.
I needed this to solve the extra `rfl` problem Kevin mentioned, but it could be deleted I just don't know what's the best to do here
changed to lemma `coe_apply`!
Is the syntax highlighting broken in vscode for the rest of this file too? If so, does adding `-- " this comment fixes the highlightin` fix it?

```suggestion
for instance, `QuaternionAlgebra.star_im` only says that the star of an imaginary quaternion
```
this PR seems to be mixing two things; can you make this generalization in a separate PR?
okay!

```suggestion
theorem coe_linearEquivTuple_symm :
    ⇑(linearEquivTuple c₁ c₂ c₃).symm = (equivTuple c₁ c₂ _).symm := rfl
```
line wrapping should break at the `:` before breaking anywhere else
I'm afraid this lemma is still bad, because the LHS is about `Quaternion` and the RHS is about `QuaternionAlgebra`. I think it should be deleted without replacement.
hmmmm okay
In fact, it's this lemma that is making the CI fail.
Yeah I guess I could delete this
I've pushed a fix that deletes the lemma
thanks!
If `k * j = c₂ * i` was true before, it can't be true now, because the meaning of c_2 has changed.

```suggestion
* `j * k = c₂ * c₃ - c₃ * i`, `k * j = c₃ * i`. -/
```

```suggestion
  (equivProd c₁ c₂ c₃).injective.addCommGroup _ rfl (fun _ _ ↦ rfl) (fun _ ↦ rfl) (fun _ _ ↦ rfl)
```
It just looks weird with 2 explicit and one implicit
Same thing here, this just looks weird with two explicit and one implicit variable
And here
etc etc

This `rfl` should not be needed. The missing lemma (which can go on line 501 or so, just after `coe_mul` is 

```
@[norm_cast, simp]
lemma coe_ofNat {n : ℕ} [n.AtLeastTwo] :
    ((ofNat(n) : R) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]) = (ofNat(n) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]) := by
  rfl
```
(thanks Bhavik!). Your refactor exposed this hole in the API.

My `ofNat` suggestion above breaks this proof, and you should fix it by making ofNat lemmas just like the natCast lemmas in line 400-440 or so:
```
@[simp]
theorem ofNat_re (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] : (ofNat(n) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]).re = ofNat(n) := rfl

@[simp]
theorem ofNat_imI (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] : (ofNat(n) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]).imI = 0 := rfl

@[simp]
theorem ofNat_imJ (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] : (ofNat(n) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]).imJ = 0 := rfl

@[simp]
theorem ofNat_imK (n : ℕ) [n.AtLeastTwo] : (ofNat(n) : ℍ[R,c₁,c₂,c₃]).imK = 0 := rfl
```
etc
What was wrong with the old proof? It's better!
